04360nam a22006375i 9781782049166DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820491667 a10.1515/97817820491662doi  a(DE-B1597)676361  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPR2045 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a823/.21 aWhetter, Kevin S, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Manuscript and Meaning of Malory's ‹i›Morte Darthur‹/i› :bRubrication, Commemoration, Memorialization /cKevin S Whetter.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2017] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b16 colour illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArthurian Studies ;v8400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPlates -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on the Text -- tA Textual Introduction -- t1 The Unusual Nature of Winchester’s Rubrication -- t2 Tracing Winchester’s Rubrication and Marginalia -- t3 Malory’s Sacralized Secularity -- t4 Rubricated Elegy -- tConclusion: The Red and the Black -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn examination of the rubricated letters in the Morte makes a convincing case for the design being by Malory himself.The red-ink names that decorate the Winchester manuscript of Malory's Morte Darthur are striking; yet until now, no-one has asked why the rubrication exists. This book explores the uniqueness and thematic significance of the physical layout of the Morte in its manuscript context, arguing that the layout suggests, and the correlations between manuscript design and narrative theme confirm, that the striking arrangement is likely to have been the product of authorial design rather than something unusual dreamed up by patron, scribe, reader, or printer. The introduction offers a thorough account of not only the textual tradition of the Morte, but also the ways in which scholarship to date has not done enough with the manuscript contexts of Malory's Arthuriad. The book then goes on to establish the singularity and likely provenance of Winchester's rubrication of names. In the second half of the study the author elucidates the narrative significance of this rubrication pattern, outlining striking connections between manuscript layout and major narrative events, characters, and themes. He suggests that the manuscript mise-en-page underscores Malory's interest in human character and knighthood, creating a memorializing function similar to the many inscribed tombs that dominate the landscape of the Morte's narrative pages. Inshort, Winchester's design creates a memorializing tomb for Arthurian chivalry. K.S. WHETTER is Professor of English at Acadia University, Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRubricationy15th century. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEnglish studies.  aMorte Darthur.  aMorte.  adesign.  adocument preservation.  amanuscript.  amedieval history.  amiddle ages.  amuseum.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204916640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782049166423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782049166/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles